  "@id": "ocp:sep/chinese-epistemology",
  "meta": {
    "title": "Epistemology in Chinese Philosophy",
    "description": "Chinese philosophy developed on the basis of ontological holism, where the internal relations of parts contribute to the dynamic structure of unfolding known as the metaphysical dao (&#36947; path, way). Its epistemology is embodied in learning and practice, guided by masters who navigate, discern, and follow the Way ( dao ). The concepts and categories used in Chinese philosophy cannot be easily transferred from one socio-cultural context into another, and it is often difficult to understand this philosophy through the lens of traditional Western epistemology of knowledge as true belief plus justification. It is therefore important to use caution so as not to diminish the richness and depth of Chinese thought or turn it into a weak version of Western philosophical thought. The epistemological dimensions of Chinese texts and their role in the context of Chinese thought has been developed increasingly successfully under the aegis of rediscovering and applying specific traditional Chinese methodological approaches and categories (Lenk and Paul 1993). The present entry similarly explores Chinese epistemology through the lens of conceptual and ideational assets created and developed in the Chinese tradition (Creller 2014: 196). According to the prevailing traditional European epistemologies, knowledge has mainly been gained through observation and reasoning. However, in traditional Chinese thought, knowledge has been understood in a much broader sense, namely as something which also (or primarily) stems from moral training and which cannot be separated from (social) practice. In this sense, the epistemological paradigms of Chinese philosophy prioritize being good-at true belief. This knowing can be experienced with perceptive insight, such as through \"illumination\" ( ming &#26126;) (Heitz 2021: 188). Concepts like truth, logos (law or logic deducing particular truths from universal propositions, and a law-like moral order in the world, are alien concepts to ancient Chinese thinkers. Their \"logicians\" did not develop a syllogistic theory of universal affirmative and negative propositions. (Yuan 2021: 193) Confucian knowing can be seen as \"an attempt to achieve optimal effect through the application of a cultivated imagination\" (Coyle 2021: 169). The notion happens to occur in the first as well as the last sayings of the Confucian Analects , which certainly indicates a certain interest in the topic by Confucius and his followers. (Defoort 2021: 153) The method which determined most of the epistemological teachings found in the Chinese classics was based on a holistic world view, and was directed towards a comprehension which could be achieved through education and learning. The basic contents of these teachings were rooted in the premises of practical concerns and pragmatic ethics. Chinese epistemology was relational (Ro&scaron;ker 2012), meaning that it understood the external world to be ordered as a network of relations, forming a dynamic structure. The human mind was also structured in accordance with this cosmic all-embracing organic system ( li &#29702;). The relational cor&shy;re&shy;spon&shy;dence and mutual compatibility between the cosmic and mental structures thus represents the basic precondition of human perception and comprehension. This entry will provide a systematic overview of the special features, the central methods and the main developmental streams of classical Chinese epistemological discourses that were based on a structurally ordered holistic worldview and rooted in axiological premises.",
    "version": "1.0.0",
    "dateCreated": "2026-03-22T05:15:16.416Z",
    "dateModified": "2026-03-22T05:15:16.416Z",
    "datePublished": "2014-09-25T14:00:00.000Z",
    "keywords": [
